04886nam a22007095i 9780691190495DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182007nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911904957 a10.1515/97806911904952doi  a(DE-B1597)501748  a(OCoLC)1044871152  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHF1536.5.F8 7aBUS0230002bisacsh04a3372231 aNye, John V. C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWar, Wine, and Taxes :bThe Political Economy of Anglo-French Trade, 1689-1900 /cJohn V. C. Nye. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Princeton Economic History of the Western World ;v2000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER 1. Problems of Perspective: The Myth of Free Trade Britain and Fortress France -- tCHAPTER 2. The History of British Economic Policy -- tCHAPTER 3. The Unbearable Lightness of Drink: Assessing the Effects of British Tariffs on French Wine -- tCHAPTER 4. The Beginnings: Trade and the Struggle for European Power in the Late 1600s -- tCHAPTER 5. Counterfactuals or What If? -- tCHAPTER 6. Wine, Beer, and Money: The Political Economy of Brewing and Eighteenth-Century British Fiscal Policy -- tCHAPTER 7. The Political Economy of Nineteenth-Century Trade -- tCHAPTER 8. Trade and Taxes in Retrospect: Were British Fiscal Exceptionalism and Economic Success Linked? -- tAPPENDIX Modeling the Effects of British and French Tariffs on National Income -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn War, Wine, and Taxes, John Nye debunks the myth that Britain was a free-trade nation during and after the industrial revolution, by revealing how the British used tariffs--notably on French wine--as a mercantilist tool to politically weaken France and to respond to pressure from local brewers and others. The book reveals that Britain did not transform smoothly from a mercantilist state in the eighteenth century to a bastion of free trade in the late nineteenth. This boldly revisionist account gives the first satisfactory explanation of Britain's transformation from a minor power to the dominant nation in Europe. It also shows how Britain and France negotiated the critical trade treaty of 1860 that opened wide the European markets in the decades before World War I. Going back to the seventeenth century and examining the peculiar history of Anglo-French military and commercial rivalry, Nye helps us understand why the British drink beer not wine, why the Portuguese sold liquor almost exclusively to Britain, and how liberal, eighteenth-century Britain managed to raise taxes at an unprecedented rate--with government revenues growing five times faster than the gross national product. War, Wine, and Taxes stands in stark contrast to standard interpretations of the role tariffs played in the economic development of Britain and France, and sheds valuable new light on the joint role of commercial and fiscal policy in the rise of the modern state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aTariff on winezGreat BritainxHistory. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691190495zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691190495423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691190495.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  